ile.  Seems fallible to me and might be a good way to frame someone.  For instance I could just steal <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>your</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> gun, go commit a crime with it, and then sneakily return the gun to the owner.  Some people who don't use their guns frequently might not even realize it's gone so they might not report it missing to the police.   Sounds like a good way to use the potential law to create frameups.  And as the segment mentioned, people could just change the barrel of the gun to defeat the measure.  Whaddya think? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 181<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/03 7:07 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=778.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: your views on 'gun fingerprinting'</span><hr size=1> Indeed, sounds like a good way to create a new criminal growth industry, the manufacture and installation of untraceable barrels. Any reasonably skilled gunsmith can make a new barrel. A gunsmith here in Lubbock did in fact make a new barrel for my antique rifle. The price was reasonable and the workmanship superb. The great majority of these people are completely honest, but a few would inevitably go over to the dark side if the price were right. I don't think an 1880s vintage military rifle is likely to be of much use to criminals, they wouldn't know how to load it for one thing, but there are plenty of guns they can steal or even buy and re-barrel. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=zaphod4468>zaphod4468</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>ezOP</span><br>  Posts: 2008<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/03 10:30 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=778.topic&index=2>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/zaphod3.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: your views on 'gun fingerprinting'</span><hr size=1> Plus it would rely on people to actually bring their existing guns in for 'fingerprinting'... which means only the law abiding citizens... the 'bad guys' wouldn't do it. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=projectorion>projectorion</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Nuclear Renaissance Man</span><br>  Posts: 3330<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/03 11:42 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=778.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://news.nationalgeographic.com/news/2001/05/images/021011_nuclear.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: your views on 'gun fingerprinting'</span><hr size=1> So stupid. Alerting people to the importance of barrels in identifying guns is madness. My cousin makes his own bullets and we discussed this years ago. Yes, it's easy to change a barrel over. Sometimes, making laws only increase law breaking. Those few cold blooded murderers that we most want to catch will realise their gun is 'known'. There will be more arrests for spur of the moment criminals who don't think about the consequences and then discover the bullet scratchings have given them away. But those people are rather sloppy and probably would have been caught anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#484848><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=hamster@nuclearspace>Hamster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 864<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/11/03 1:29 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=778.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Re: your views on 'gun fingerprinting'</span><hr size=1> I hadn't thought about the headaches such a law could create for gunsmiths in particular.  I live two doors down from a gunsmith and I think I'll go bring this up.  Everytime they repair a gun or replace a barrel will they have to go through two thousand miles of red tape when refinishing or replacing barrels?  Another thing, even 60 Minutes brought up the fact that it's not an exact science using ballistic markings to identify guns.  It's not uncommon for guns to have fairly similiar prints.  Someone would have to be hired to manually scan through matches reduced by computer analysis to determine which gun the bullet came from which means more tax money and more errors.  Ultimately, I agree with Zaphod, the people who intend to use their guns for criminal purposes won't show up so Big Brother can harass their gun rights.  I just don't see gang bangers taking a day off from dope dealing to have their guns cataloged.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub97.ezboard.com/bnuclearspace.showUserPublicProfile?gid=atomicconspiracy>Atomic Conspiracy</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Moderator</span><br>  Posts: 185<br> <font color=#6F6F6F>(2/12/03 7:06 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub97.ezboard.com/fnuclearspacefrm1.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=778.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> <img src="http://www.nuclearspace.com/ezboard/images/posticons/7.gif" align=absmiddle>  Batcave update: School board bans &quot;gun&quot; from spell</span><hr size=1> Tsk, tsk, what would George Orwell think? Thought y'all might want to see this:<!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.worldnetdaily.com/news/article.asp?ARTICLE_ID=30990">Source</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><br>
